    %section
      %h1 What is a gold?
      %p
        Gold is a precious metal. However in India it is more than just a precious metal. Gold is part of culture and history. Centuries ago, kings and rulers used gold as a medium of exchange to pay royalties to each other. Gold coins were used as local currency. Even in Europe, the quest for gold led to the exploration of the western hemisphere. In today’s world, many countries issue their currency against gold reserves. Thus gold has a very important role to play. Indian investors still invest in gold largely in form jewellery and coins rather than modern investment avenues like ETFs and mutual funds.
    %section
      %h1 How risky is gold?
      %p
        Gold in India is considered less risky than stocks but more risky than fixed deposits. However, for all practical purposes, given the high inflation and current account deficit in India, gold is quite safe for the retail investor.
    %section
      %h1 Gold as an investment
      %ol
        %li
          %b
            Gold is a hedge against inflation:
          Gold has been a preserver of value through time. It has served as a natural hedge to inflation. As the inflation of a country goes up, the price of gold also climbs.
        %li
          %b
            Gold is a safe haven in times of uncertainty:
          Gold also serves a safe harbour and investors of all kinds flock to investing in gold during times of economic and political uncertainties. Example: In August 2011 when S&P downgraded Unites States of America, in matter of 2 weeks, gold rallied almost 10% from approx. Rs. 25,500 to Rs 28,000 (per 10 grams).
        %li
          %b
            Gold is quoted in US dollars globally and is subject to currency risk:
          Globally, gold is quoted in US dollars. The gold price in rupees is calculated by multiplying the gold price in dollars by the exchange rate between dollars and rupees. Thus when the exchange rate between USD and rupee changes, it has a bearing on price of gold in Rupees too. Example: From April 1st 2012 to May 1st 2012, gold in USD changed by -0.83%, however gold in rupees increased by 2.31%. The difference in the two prices can be explained by change in exchange rate of USD vs INR which rose from Rs 50.87  per dollar to Rs 52.51 per dollar. Similarly if the exchange rate of INR vs USD were to decrease and price of gold in the international market were to be constant, you could witness a decrease in price of gold in India. 
