    %section
      %h1 How to invest in gold?
      %p
        People in India traditionally bought gold in the physical form i.e. jewellery, coins, biscuits, bars etc. Relatively new methods involve investing via gold exchange traded funds (ETF) and
        #{link_to 'mutual funds', main_app.page_path('investment_education/mutual-funds-etf')}
        dedicated to investing in gold. E.g. Goldman Sachs Gold Exchange Traded Scheme (Goldbees), Kotak Gold ETF, Reliance Gold Savings Fund.
      %h1 Investing in Gold ETFs and Gold Mutual Funds
      %p
        Investing in Gold ETF s / Gold Mutual Funds give you the following benefits over investing in physical gold:
      %ol
        %li
          %b
            Smaller denominations:
          Investors can invest as little as few hundreds depending on the face value of units issued by ETFs. ETFs unit value (at time of issue) can vary from Rs 100 to Rs 3000 or even higher than that.
        %li
          %b
            Better Liquidity:
          ETFs are and mutual funds are traded on exchanges and it is extremely easy to increase or decrease your position. Moreover the trades take place immediately and the amount is either debited (in case you purchase) or credited (in case you sell) to/from your demat account. Note: When you sell an ETF or your mutual fund holding, it usually takes around 2-3 days for the money to be credited in your demat account and  probably another day from your demat account to your bank account. Thus in case of an emergency, you decide to sell your holdings in ETFs and Mutual funds though you will be able to transact immediately, it might still take 5-6 days before you get your money.
        %li
          %b
            Reduced transaction and holding cost:
          While purchasing gold in physical form you incur expenses like making charges (for jewellery), sales tax, VAT etc. However while investing via ETFs and mutual funds, you only pay a nominal brokerage charge and some related transaction charges such as STT (Securities and Transaction Tax).
        %li
          %b
            Safety:
          Since investment in gold ETFs/Mutual Funds are held in the demat form and not in physical form, it cannot be stolen. You also save on the additional holding cost such as bank locker charges you might incur if you were to invest in the physical form.
        %li
          %b
            Tax Benefits:
          When you invest in gold ETFs and mutual funds, if your holding period is above one year you are subject to long term capital gain tax which at present is nil. If you were to hold the same investment in the physical form, you get this tax benefit only for a holding period of 3 years or more. Note that short term capital gain is subject to 15% tax. You also do not pay any wealth tax in case of demat holdings.
    %section
      %h1 Editor’s take
      %p
        Gold is a fantastic investment in the Indian context (high inflation) and should be part of every investor’s portfolio. Gold is not highly correlated to stocks, bonds or other assets. Hence it serves as a classic
        #{link_to 'diversification', main_app.page_path('investment_education/investment-diversification')}
        asset. We advise investing in gold ETFs and gold Mutual funds as opposed to physical gold.
